Hypothesis 1

friends_vs_happiness <- responses %>% select(Number.of.friends, Happiness.in.life) %>% arrange(desc(Number.of.friends))
head(friends_vs_happiness)
##   Number.of.friends Happiness.in.life
## 1                 5                 5
## 2                 5                 5
## 3                 5                 4
## 4                 5                 4
## 5                 5                 4
## 6                 5                 2
xyplot( Number.of.friends ~ Happiness.in.life, data = friends_vs_happiness, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE)

Most people are moderately happy with a moderate amount of friends. There are few people who are very happy with a small amount of friends. But, having more friends usually leads to greater happiness.

Hypothesis 2

gender_vs_happiness <- select(responses, Gender, Happiness.in.life)
head(gender_vs_happiness)
##   Gender Happiness.in.life
## 1 female                 4
## 2 female                 4
## 3 female                 4
## 4 female                 2
## 5 female                 3
## 6   male                 3
bwplot(Happiness.in.life ~ Gender, data = gender_vs_happiness, main="") 

There are no observable differences between males and females in terms of happiness. However, people who didn't note their gender on the survey are slightly less happy.

Hypothesis 3

happiness_vs_age <- (responses %>% select(Age, Happiness.in.life) %>% na.omit() %>% group_by(Age) %>% summarise(avg_happiness= mean(Happiness.in.life)))
head(happiness_vs_age)
## # A tibble: 6  2
##     Age avg_happiness
##   <int>         <dbl>
## 1    15      3.600000
## 2    16      3.379310
## 3    17      3.566038
## 4    18      3.747967
## 5    19      3.765550
## 6    20      3.726804
xyplot( avg_happiness ~ Age, data = happiness_vs_age, main="") 

Generally, people get happier as they grow older.

Hypothesis 4

empathy_vs_social <- (responses %>% select(Empathy, Socializing) %>% arrange(desc(Empathy)))
xyplot( Empathy ~ Socializing, data = empathy_vs_social, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE) 

We plotted empathy versus socializing. On the survey, people were asked to rate how empathetic they think they are and how much they enjoy meeting new people. We found that self-described highly empathetic people enjoy meeting new people a moderate amount. Unsurprisingly, non-empathetic people don't enjoy socializing very much.

Hypothesis 5

reliability_vs_achievements <- (responses %>% select(Reliability, Achievements, Age) %>% filter(Age > 22))
xyplot( Reliability ~ Achievements, data = reliability_vs_achievements, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE) 

reliability_vs_achievements2 <- (responses %>% select(Reliability, Achievements, Age) %>% filter(Age < 22))
xyplot( Reliability ~ Achievements, data = reliability_vs_achievements2, main="", jitter.x=TRUE, jitter.y=TRUE) 

In the first graph, we plotted reliability versus achievements, filtering out people younger than 22 years old. We found that highly reliable people were moderately to less likely to boast of their achievements. Unreliable people were less likely to brag about their achievements. In the second graph, we plotted the same thing, but for people younger than 22. We found that younger people were more likely to brag about their achievements, even if they were only moderately reliable.

Hypothesis 6

assertiveness_vs_gender <- (responses %>% select(Gender, Assertiveness) %>% na.omit %>% group_by(Gender))
bwplot( Assertiveness ~ Gender, data = assertiveness_vs_gender, main="") 

We plotted assertiveness versus gender and found that women were slightly more likely than men to say that they were more assertive.
